00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,120
This is a full wave bridge rectifier.

2
00:00:03,640 --> 00:00:06,180
It's used to power electronic circuits,

3
00:00:06,740 --> 00:00:10,480
so we're going to learn in detail how they work in this video.

4
00:00:11,260 --> 00:00:14,440
Electricity is dangerous and can be fatal.

5
00:00:14,680 --> 00:00:18,500
You must be qualified and competent to carry out any electrical work.

6
00:00:19,460 --> 00:00:21,920
Full bridge rectifiers look like this.

7
00:00:22,500 --> 00:00:23,940
There are many shapes and sizes,

8
00:00:24,400 --> 00:00:28,600
but they essentially consist of four diodes in a certain arrangement.

9
00:00:28,600 --> 00:00:32,440
They are usually aligned in a diamond configuration,

10
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:35,980
but they can be aligned in other ways such as these.

11
00:00:37,100 --> 00:00:41,380
We typically find them represented on engineering drawings like this,

12
00:00:42,120 --> 00:00:44,080
this being the symbol for a diode.

13
00:00:44,920 --> 00:00:48,060
The arrow points in the direction of conventional current.

14
00:00:48,760 --> 00:00:54,460
This shows that AC electricity is the input and DC electricity is the output.

15
00:00:54,460 --> 00:01:01,860
The full bridge rectifier converts AC alternating current into DC direct current.

16
00:01:02,660 --> 00:01:03,580
Why is that important?

17
00:01:04,120 --> 00:01:07,680
Because the power outlets in our homes provide AC,

18
00:01:08,180 --> 00:01:10,880
but our electrical devices use DC,

19
00:01:11,360 --> 00:01:15,360
so we need to convert the AC into DC electricity.

20
00:01:15,360 --> 00:01:20,840
For example, a laptop charger takes AC from the power outlet

21
00:01:20,840 --> 00:01:24,460
and converts this to DC to power the laptop.

22
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:29,840
If you look at the power adapter for your laptop and other electronic devices,

23
00:01:30,320 --> 00:01:34,420
the manufacturer's label tells you it's converting AC to DC.

24
00:01:34,420 --> 00:01:41,220
In this example, it states that it needs an input of between 100 and 240 volts

25
00:01:41,220 --> 00:01:43,580
with the symbol for AC electricity,

26
00:01:43,580 --> 00:01:46,920
and this will draw 1.5 amps of current.

27
00:01:47,620 --> 00:01:52,300
It will then output 19.5 volts of DC electricity

28
00:01:52,300 --> 00:01:55,520
and 3.33 amps of current.

29
00:01:56,080 --> 00:01:59,920
Notice that it also states 50 to 60 hertz.

30
00:01:59,920 --> 00:02:04,480
This is the AC frequency and we'll look at that in just a moment.

31
00:02:05,480 --> 00:02:10,320
In AC electricity, the voltage and current constantly change direction

32
00:02:10,320 --> 00:02:12,360
between forwards and backwards.

33
00:02:13,060 --> 00:02:16,880
That's because there's a magnetic field in the AC generator

34
00:02:16,880 --> 00:02:21,020
which essentially pushes and pulls electrons in the wires.

35
00:02:21,860 --> 00:02:26,240
This is therefore changing between positive and negative values

36
00:02:26,240 --> 00:02:28,400
as it flows forwards and backwards.

37
00:02:28,400 --> 00:02:31,080
The voltage is not constant

38
00:02:31,080 --> 00:02:34,780
even though the multimeter will make it look like it is.

39
00:02:35,440 --> 00:02:38,620
If we plotted this, we get a sine wave pattern.

40
00:02:39,640 --> 00:02:44,260
The voltage changes between a peak positive and a peak negative value

41
00:02:44,260 --> 00:02:47,440
as the maximum intensity of the magnetic field

42
00:02:47,440 --> 00:02:51,060
passes the coils of wire inside the AC generator.

43
00:02:51,740 --> 00:02:55,760
This example reaches 170 volts at its peaks.

44
00:02:55,760 --> 00:02:58,000
So if we plotted these values,

45
00:02:58,440 --> 00:03:02,740
we have positive and negative peaks of 170 volts.

46
00:03:03,300 --> 00:03:07,560
If we took the average of these values, we would get 0 volts.

47
00:03:08,180 --> 00:03:09,520
That's not very useful.

48
00:03:10,020 --> 00:03:14,500
So a clever engineer decided to use the root mean squared voltage.

49
00:03:14,500 --> 00:03:17,180
That is what our multimeters calculate

50
00:03:17,180 --> 00:03:19,880
when we connect them to the electrical outlets.

51
00:03:20,880 --> 00:03:22,240
To find the peak voltage,

52
00:03:22,640 --> 00:03:25,120
we multiply the root mean squared voltage

53
00:03:25,120 --> 00:03:26,940
by the square root of 2,

54
00:03:27,480 --> 00:03:29,640
which is roughly 1.41.

55
00:03:30,180 --> 00:03:32,300
To find the RMS voltage,

56
00:03:32,720 --> 00:03:36,600
we divide the peak voltage by 0.707.

57
00:03:36,600 --> 00:03:40,100
For example, here I have a North American,

58
00:03:40,640 --> 00:03:43,820
British, Australian and European power outlets.

59
00:03:44,460 --> 00:03:47,720
This multimeter shows basic waveforms

60
00:03:47,720 --> 00:03:49,480
and when I connect to any of these

61
00:03:49,480 --> 00:03:51,220
between the phase and neutral,

62
00:03:51,740 --> 00:03:53,000
we see a sine wave,

63
00:03:53,540 --> 00:03:56,140
which is indicating this is AC electricity.

64
00:03:56,980 --> 00:04:01,200
Notice that the British and European outlets are 230 volts.

65
00:04:01,200 --> 00:04:04,540
The Australian outlet is 240 volts,

66
00:04:04,920 --> 00:04:08,620
but all three of these are at a frequency of 50 hertz.

67
00:04:09,380 --> 00:04:13,440
However, the North American outlets read 120 volts

68
00:04:13,440 --> 00:04:15,840
at a frequency of 60 hertz.

69
00:04:16,540 --> 00:04:19,080
The frequency is measured in hertz,

70
00:04:19,640 --> 00:04:22,000
but this just means the sine wave is repeating

71
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:26,320
60 times per second in the North American electrical systems

72
00:04:26,320 --> 00:04:29,840
and 50 times per second in the rest of the world.

73
00:04:31,420 --> 00:04:34,500
The voltage is lower in the North American system

74
00:04:34,500 --> 00:04:36,660
at 120 volts,

75
00:04:37,240 --> 00:04:40,600
whereas it's 230 to 240 volts

76
00:04:40,600 --> 00:04:41,900
in the rest of the world,

77
00:04:42,500 --> 00:04:43,960
although there are some exceptions,

78
00:04:44,300 --> 00:04:45,780
but we won't go into that in this video.

79
00:04:46,440 --> 00:04:48,720
The peak voltage of each electrical system

80
00:04:48,720 --> 00:04:50,480
is therefore as follows.

81
00:04:51,260 --> 00:04:52,520
In DC electricity,

82
00:04:53,060 --> 00:04:54,460
the voltage is constant

83
00:04:54,460 --> 00:04:55,920
and in the positive region.

84
00:04:56,320 --> 00:04:58,680
The electrons do not reverse.

85
00:04:59,020 --> 00:05:01,200
They all flow in just one direction.

86
00:05:02,200 --> 00:05:03,880
So if I measure this battery,

87
00:05:04,380 --> 00:05:07,020
we see a flat line in the positive region

88
00:05:07,020 --> 00:05:09,260
at around 1.5 volts.

89
