at around 4 volts on the multimeter.

93
00:05:21,700 --> 00:05:25,400
We can use this adapter to measure a USB port.

94
00:05:26,320 --> 00:05:29,380
We can see it's providing around 5 volts DC.

95
00:05:29,380 --> 00:05:32,580
And if we plot this with the other multimeter,

96
00:05:33,200 --> 00:05:36,060
we again see a constant flat line

97
00:05:36,060 --> 00:05:38,700
indicating this is DC electricity.

98
00:05:39,860 --> 00:05:42,400
This is a four-wave bridge rectifier.

99
00:05:42,400 --> 00:05:44,360
On these input terminals,

100
00:05:44,360 --> 00:05:48,000
we see around 12 volts AC with a sine wave.

101
00:05:48,960 --> 00:05:50,420
And on these output terminals,

102
00:05:50,420 --> 00:05:53,420
we see around 14 volts of DC.

103
00:05:54,080 --> 00:05:57,780
So this device is converting AC to DC.

104
00:05:58,280 --> 00:06:00,980
The voltage is slightly higher on the output

105
00:06:00,980 --> 00:06:02,420
because of the capacitor.

106
00:06:02,420 --> 00:06:06,020
And we'll see why that is later on in this video.

107
00:06:06,820 --> 00:06:08,360
Now, you need to remember

108
00:06:08,360 --> 00:06:12,240
that rectifiers will only convert AC to DC.

109
00:06:12,900 --> 00:06:15,540
It cannot convert DC into AC.

110
00:06:16,100 --> 00:06:18,060
For that, we would need an inverter

111
00:06:18,060 --> 00:06:20,840
which uses special electronic components

112
00:06:20,840 --> 00:06:22,060
to achieve that,

113
00:06:22,440 --> 00:06:24,280
but we won't cover that in this video.

114
